<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-08-09T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-08-09T15:00:00-05:00" n="390" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d390">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.041/3: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-08-09T16:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">August 9,
                                        1927—4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>120. Your 184, July 31, 4 p.m. The Department perceives no occasion now
                            to question on the grounds of <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> character
                            of courts legality of acts of Supreme Court or Court of Appeals whose
                            judges were replaced by <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> authorities.
                            Your citation to Cooley considered in point. See also volume one,
                            Moore’s <hi rend="italic">Digest</hi>, page 54, <hi rend="italic">et
                                seq.</hi></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>